50|$|Although Cooper pairing is {{a quantum}} effect, {{the reason for}} the pairing can be seen from a {{simplified}} classical explanation. An electron in a metal normally behaves as a free particle. The electron is repelled from other electrons due to their negative charge, but it also attracts the positive ions that make up the rigid lattice of the metal. This attraction distorts the <b>ion</b> <b>lattice,</b> moving the ions slightly toward the electron, increasing the positive charge density of the lattice in the vicinity. This positive charge can attract other electrons. At long distances, this attraction between electrons due to the displaced ions can overcome the electrons' repulsion due to their negative charge, and cause them to pair up. The rigorous quantum mechanical explanation shows that the effect is due to electron-phonon interactions, with the phonon being the collective motion of the positively-charged lattice.|$|E
